          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Hungary to lose a billion</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Hungary <a href="https://www.euronews.com/my-europe/2024/06/21/why-is-the-far-right-gaining-popularity-among-young-people" target="_Blank">risks</a> losing over a billion dollars in EU funding allocated for poorer regions unless it completes 17 key reforms related to anti-corruption and conflict-of-interest laws by December 31, 2024. The European Commission has frozen over $17 billion in grants, pressuring Prime Minister Viktor Orbán to address rule-of-law concerns. Failure to meet these demands within the two-year reclaim period would mean the funds are permanently forfeited.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Hungary’s economic growth is well below the EU average, while its government deficit as a proportion of GDP is the highest in the bloc. Budget Commissioner Piotr Serafin said that the measures taken by the government are “not quite what we were hoping for.” Separately, Hungary is trying to unblock the Erasmus student exchange funds and research grants by removing the political figures from the public body overseeing most universities. However, the commission said this move will not affect the remaining frozen funds.</p>
        </mj-text>
