          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><strong>🇸🇾 Syria:</strong>    
          Islamist-led rebels, including Hayat Tahrir al-Sham (HTS), have <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/syria-islamist-rebels-eye-more-gains-after-seizing-hama/a-70966612" target="_Blank">captured</a> Hama city, a strategically vital area connecting Damascus to Aleppo and the coast, following a surprise offensive. HTS, an al-Qaeda offshoot with Turkish ties, aims to advance further south toward <a href="https://www.google.com/maps/place/Homs%E2%80%8E,+Syria/@34.730411,36.5946811,12z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m6!3m5!1s0x15230e9047c7c0fb:0xac367e06303788d0!8m2!3d34.7325256!4d36.713452!16zL20vMGs5cWY?entry=ttu&g_ep=EgoyMDI0MTIwMy4wIKXMDSoASAFQAw%3D%3D" target="_Blank">Homs</a>. The Syrian army, backed by Russian airstrikes, continues intense battles across Hama province, which serves as an essential base of support for President Bashar al-Assad and its connection to critical transport routes.</p>
        </mj-text>
